# Summary
Introduced bug: the auto-photo feature is activated from untrusted/imported configuration during application startup instead of only after the user saves/enables the setting in the normal trusted config flow. The introduced watcher also forces uploads for matched files, creating an unintended data-exfiltration path.
This commit adds AutoPhoto settings and starts the watcher unconditionally from App.startup whenever cfg.AutoPhoto.Enabled is true. The existing startup path allows a single .json argument to be loaded into settings mode for editing/review. Because startup calls restartAutoPhotoWatcher regardless of the current UI mode or whether the config has been saved/confirmed, an attacker can supply a JSON config with autoPhoto.enabled=true, autoPhoto.photoDirectory set to a sensitive or broad image directory, and autoPhoto.webhookUrl or discord.webhookUrl set to an attacker-controlled Discord webhook or compatible upload endpoint. Once the UI opens, the watcher recursively scans the configured directory and processes newly appearing image files. The process path forcibly enables Discord upload and substitutes the auto-photo webhook if present, so future VRChat photos or other newly created supported images are automatically uploaded without an explicit processing action by the user. Existing files are marked as seen on watcher startup, so this primarily affects new files created after opening the config, but it still violates user consent and can leak private photos/paths while the user is merely reviewing settings.

# Validation
## Rubric
- [x] Imported single-JSON configuration can populate state.Config while the app is only in settings/review mode before user save or confirmation.
- [x] App startup starts AutoPhoto based solely on cfg.AutoPhoto.Enabled, without checking whether the config is trusted/saved or whether state.Mode is settings.
- [x] The watcher monitors the attacker-controlled photoDirectory and processes newly created supported image files.
- [x] AutoPhoto processing forces Discord upload and replaces the webhook with autoPhoto.webhookUrl, even when normal output.uploadDiscord is false.
- [x] A local attacker-controlled webhook receives the automatically uploaded newly created image, demonstrating the unintended exfiltration path.
## Report
Validated. I first checked the relevant code paths: src/main.go:45-56 loads a single .json argument into state.Config, sets state.Mode=ModeSettings, and opens the UI without requiring save/confirmation; src/app.go:41-43 calls restartAutoPhotoWatcher(a.state.Config) during startup; src/app.go:349-374 starts the watcher whenever cfg.AutoPhoto.Enabled is true with no mode/trust check; src/internal/appcore/config.go:39-43 and 78-90 load autoPhoto.enabled, photoDirectory, and webhookUrl directly from JSON; src/internal/appcore/autophoto.go:24-36 starts by scanning the configured directory, 41-51 processes newly appearing files, 67-73 forces cfg.Output.UploadDiscord=true and substitutes cfg.AutoPhoto.WebhookURL, and 83-99 recursively scans supported images; src/internal/appcore/processor.go:91-95 then calls UploadDiscord. Dynamic PoC: I added a targeted Go test artifact. TestPoCImportedConfigStartupStartsWatcherInSettingsMode simulates the imported .json settings/review state and calls App.startup; output shows: startup accepted imported config in ModeSettings and started watcher for /tmp/.../sensitive_photos. TestPoCAutoPhotoWatcherForcesUploadToConfigWebhook uses the same malicious config shape with output.uploadDiscord=false and a local httptest webhook, creates secret.png after watcher startup, and captured: POST /api/webhooks/attacker/token?wait=true ... contains_secret_name=true, with handler result URL=https://cdn.example/secret.png. This proves new files in the attacker-selected directory are automatically exfiltrated to the configured webhook despite normal Discord upload being disabled. Crash attempt: this is a logic/consent bug, so no memory-safety crash is expected; the direct PoC reproduces by successful unintended upload rather than crash. Valgrind was unavailable in the container; go test -asan reproduced the same functional behavior and passed, confirming no sanitizer crash was needed. Debugger validation: an LLDB trace on a debug test binary hit App.startup at app.go:42, App.restartAutoPhotoWatcher at app.go:349 from startup at app.go:43, AutoPhotoWatcher.process at autophoto.go:67 through tick/Run, and UploadDiscord at discord.go:30 through Processor.processImage at processor.go:94 and AutoPhotoWatcher.process at autophoto.go:73. This confirms the runtime chain.

# Evidence
src/app.go (L349 to 374)
  Note: The watcher is started whenever cfg.AutoPhoto.Enabled is true and updates history/results from a background goroutine; there is no check that the user has saved or confirmed the imported settings.
```
func (a *App) restartAutoPhotoWatcher(cfg appcore.Config) {
	if a.autoCancel != nil {
		a.autoCancel()
		a.autoCancel = nil
	}
	if a.ctx == nil || !cfg.AutoPhoto.Enabled {
		return
	}
	ctx, cancel := context.WithCancel(a.ctx)
	a.autoCancel = cancel
	watcher := appcore.AutoPhotoWatcher{
		Config: cfg,
		Handler: func(event appcore.AutoPhotoEvent) {
			if event.Result.URL != "" && event.Result.Error == "" {
				results := []appcore.Result{event.Result}
				if history, err := appcore.AddResultsToHistory(appcore.HistoryPath(a.configPath), results); err == nil {
					a.state.History = history
					event.Result = results[0]
				}
			}
			a.state.Results = append([]appcore.Result{event.Result}, a.state.Results...)
			a.state.Mode = appcore.ModeResults
			runtime.EventsEmit(a.ctx, "auto-photo:result", event)
		},
	}
	go watcher.Run(ctx)
```

